# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: banana-chips
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:banana-chips/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] A **3-in-1**, **trio** or **three-in-one** is a fast-food dish consisting of chips, boiled rice (or egg fried rice), and curry sauce served in a single foil tray or plastic container.
[src:banana-chips/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It became popular in Ireland as a dish from chip shops and Chinese restaurants in the early twenty-first century.
[src:banana-chips/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] It developed a cult following in the 2010s, and media outlets debated the merits of it compared to a spice bag, which became popular around the same time.
[src:banana-chips/3-in-1-fast-food-dish] Related dishes (four-, five-in one) contain additional ingredients such as chicken balls, or chicken or beef pieces.
[src:banana-chips/afritada] The name *afritada* is derived from Spanish *fritada* ("fried"), referring to the first step of the preparation in which the meat is pan-fried before simmering in the tomato sauce.
[src:banana-chips/afritada] Filipino *menudo* and *kaldereta* both use tomato sauce or banana ketchup.
[src:banana-chips/afritada] However, *menudo* includes sliced liver, while *kaldereta* exclusively uses goat meat or occasionally beef.
[src:banana-chips/afritada] *Igado* contains liver but no tomato sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agedashi-dōfu] While *agedashi dōfu* is the best-known *agedashi* dish, some other dishes may be prepared with similar techniques.
[src:banana-chips/agedashi-dōfu] These include *agedashinasu* (揚げ出し茄子), using eggplant.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour dishes, sauces, and cooking methods have a long history in China.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] One of the earliest recordings of sweet and sour may come from *Shaowei Yanshi Dan* (Chinese: 燒尾宴食單; pinyin: *shāowěi yànshí dān*), a menu of the food served in Tang dynasty (618–907) "Shaowei banquet" festivals written in 708.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] It included many sweet and sour adjacent dishes and recorded that they were invented by Chancellor Wei Juyuan under Emperor Zhongzong of Tang when he hosted the Emperor at his house.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Some authors say that the original sweet and sour sauce (Chinese: 糖醋醬; pinyin: *tángcùjiàng*) came from the Chinese province of Henan, but the sauce in this area is a light vinegar and sugar mixture not resembling what most people, including the Chinese, would call sweet and sour.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Many places in China use a sweet and sour sauce as a dipping sauce for fish and meat rather than in cooking, as is common in Westernized Chinese cuisine.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] This style of using sauces is popular amongst Chinese who tie certain sauces to particular meats such as chili and soy for shrimp and vinegar and garlic for goose.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] There are, however, some dishes, such as the Cantonese sweet and sour pork or loong har kow (sweet and sour lobster balls), in which the meat is cooked and a sauce added to the wok before serving.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Not all dishes are cooked; some, such as "sweet and sour fruit and vegetable" salad from the eastern regions of China, also find their way in Chinese cuisine.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] This cold dish combines salad vegetables such as cucumber, tomato, bell pepper, and onion with a mixture of pineapple (or pear), vinegar, and sugar.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In China, the sauces are traditionally made by mixing sugar or honey with a sour liquid such as rice vinegar or soy sauce and spices such as ginger and cloves.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Sometimes a paste made from tomatoes is used, but this is rare and normally restricted to Western cooking.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Cantonese sweet and sour sauce is the direct ancestor of the sauce of the same name in the West and was originally developed for sweet and sour pork.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The late Hong Kong chef Leung King included the following as his sweet and sour sauce recipe: white rice vinegar, salt, Chinese brown candy, ketchup, Worcestershire sauce, and dark soy sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] He suggests the more acidic white rice vinegar could be replaced with apple cider vinegar and that ketchup and Worcestershire sauce should be of renowned gourmet brands.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The original Cantonese sweet and sour pork (traditional Chinese: 咕嚕肉; simplified Chinese: 咕噜肉; pinyin: *gūlūròu*; Cantonese Yale: *gūlōuyuhk*; lit.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] 'rumbling meat') is made with vinegar, preserved plums and hawthorn candy for an almost scarlet color and sweet-sour taste.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] A related Hong Kong/Cantonese-based dish is sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 生炒排骨; pinyin: *Shēngchǎo páigǔ*; Cantonese Yale: *sāangcháau pàaigwāt*; lit.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The methods used are identical, with spareribs used instead of pork loin.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] A similar dish is gu lao rou or sweet and sour pork.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Originating in Suzhou, Jiangsu province, the squirrel-shaped Mandarin fish (Chinese: 松鼠鱖魚; pinyin: *Sōngshǔ Guìyú*) has a crisp skin but soft center.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The fish body of *Siniperca chuatsi* is scored such that it fans out when cooked, similar in appearance to a bushy squirrel tail.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The fish is served with a sweet and sour sauce drizzled on top and garnished with a little shrimp meat and dried bamboo shoots.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] A specialty of Shandong province, in particular the city of Jinan, the Yellow River carp is prepared by making diagonal slices partway through its flesh.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] It is next coated in corn flour, then deep-fried, causing the fish to curl and the slices to open out.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Finally, a sweet and sour sauce is poured over the cooked fish.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] This is one of the distinctive dishes typical of Shandong cuisine.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] A popular dish in Shanghai cuisine, sweet and sour spare ribs (Chinese: 糖醋小排; pinyin: *tángcù xiǎopái*) are made using pork ribs that are lightly coated in cornstarch and seasoned before being fried and served in a sweet and sour sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In South Korea, a sweet and sour meat dish known as *tangsuyuk* (탕수육; 糖水肉) is one of the most popular Korean Chinese dishes.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Made with either pork or beef, the bite-sized pieces are usually coated with potato/sweet potato starch/cornstarch or glutinous rice flour and double-fried in oil.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The dish is served with sweet and sour sauce, typically made by boiling vinegar, sugar, and water with a variety of fruits and vegetables like carrot, cucumber, onion, wood ear mushroom, and pineapple.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Starch slurry is used to thicken the sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The traditional Dalmatian dish Pašticada features prunes and sweet dessert wine (prošek) as the sweet components, and vinegar in the marinade for sourness.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour sauces have been used in English cuisine since the Middle Ages, with recipes for sweet and sour meat and fish in the 1390 cookery book *The Forme of Cury*.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, a sweet and sour sauce base made from sugar and vinegar is a gastrique.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] *Aigre-doux* is a sweet and sour sauce in general.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] According to food writer Arthur Schwartz, within Neapolitan cooking, sweet and sour was the dominant food pairing before the introduction of the tomato and the mass-uptake of pasta.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Preparations using the combination eaten in the modern cuisine include sweet and sour eggplant, but it is never used to flavour pasta dishes.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In Filipino cuisine, sweet and sour sauces are known as **agre dulce** or **Filipino sweet and sour sauce**.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] They are made by mixing cornstarch with water, salt, sugar, and a tangy ingredient (typically tomato ketchup, banana ketchup, or pineapples).
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The mixture is brought to a boil then simmered until it thickens.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The name means "sour-sweet" in Philippine Spanish, from Spanish *agrio* ("sour") and *dulce* ("sweet").
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] It is also known as *agri dulci* in Chavacano and the phrase can refer to dishes cooked with the sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] *Agre dulce* is commonly used as a dipping sauce for appetizers like *lumpia* or *okoy*.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour chicken is a dish frequently served in Chinese restaurants in various countries in Oceania, Europe, North America, and South America and available at some restaurants in East Asia and Southeast Asia in an essentially identical version.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The dish generally comprises cubes of white meat chicken deep-fried in batter and served with sweet and sour sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Sometimes it is topped with pineapple, green pepper, carrot, or sweet pickles.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Sweet and sour pork is a Chinese dish particularly popular in Westernized Cantonese cuisine and may be found worldwide.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Several provinces in China produce various dishes that claim to be the ancestor, including a traditional Jiangsu dish called "pork in a sugar and vinegar sauce" (糖醋里脊; pinyin: táng cù lǐjǐ).
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The dish consists of deep-fried pork cut into bite-sized pieces and subsequently stir-fried in a more customized version of sweet and sour sauce made of sugar, ketchup, white vinegar, and soy sauce and additional ingredients including pineapple, green pepper (capsicum), and onion.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In more elaborate preparations, the dish's tartness is controlled by requiring that Chinese white rice vinegar be used sparingly and using ketchups with less vinegary tastes, while some restaurants use unripe kiwifruits and HP sauce in place of vinegar.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Western cultures use sweet and sour sauce in two different ways.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Dishes can either include the sauce as an ingredient in cooking or use the sauce as a pour-over or dipping sauce for the meal.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Chinese restaurants in Western countries commonly serve battered and deep-fried chicken, pork, or shrimp with a sweet and sour sauce poured on top.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] It is also common to find the sweet and sour sauce cooked with sliced green peppers, onions, and pineapple before it is poured over the meat.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Many Western dishes involve cooking the meat with a variety of ingredients to make a complete sweet and sour dish in the manner of gu lo yuk.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] The most popular dishes are those of pork and shrimp.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In French cuisine, it has been developed contrary to traditional French cooking practices, and the preparation of sweet and sour sauce (Aigre-douce) often involves immersing the food in a plentiful amount of sauce.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Common in Western sweet and sour sauce is the addition of fruits such as pineapple and vegetables such as sweet pepper and green onions.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Traditional rice vinegar is becoming more readily available due to the increase in Asian food stores but a mixture of vinegar and dry sherry is often still used in sweet and sour dishes.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Also common is the use of cornstarch as a thickener for the sauce and tomato ketchup to give a stronger red color to the dish and to add a Western taste.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Most supermarkets across Europe and North America carry a range of prepared sweet and sour sauces for adding to stir-fry or dipping.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Primarily in North America, sweet and sour sauce is available as a dipping sauce at Chinese takeout establishments in small plastic packets or containers.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] In Britain, Thai-style sweet chili sauce has recently overtaken the previous popularity of Chinese-style sweet and sour sauce to the extent it can often be found at non-Asian establishments for a wide variety of Western-style snacks from fishcakes to chips and seafood such as calamari and prawns.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] A number of variations are used in barbecue cuisine, either homemade or prepared from a number of common brands.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] Besides American Chinese restaurants, popular fast food restaurants such as McDonald's, Burger King, and Wendy's carry their own proprietary brands of sweet and sour sauce packets.
[src:banana-chips/agre-dulce] These are commonly offered and used as a dipping sauce for chicken fingers and chicken nuggets.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] It is made with ground lean pork, ground pork fat, brown sugar, coarse salt, saltpeter, black pepper, bay leaf, vinegar, and garlic in hog casings.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] It is slightly sour, garlicky taste, typically bright yellow or orange due to the use of *achuete* seeds, made in bite-sized pieces.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is named after the Spanish “longaniza,” and is sometimes used interchangeably with the chorizo.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] The longganisa is a type of local sausage with two major types—the recado, with a more savory flavor, and the hamonado, with a sweet taste.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] Unlike other longganisa variants, the Alaminos longganisa's segments of the sausage are uniquely divided by small pieces of coconut leaf midribs (sometimes mistaken for toothpicks), making it easily identifiable.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] Each sausage string usually has six segments and is traditionally tied at the end with a length of buli palm fiber.
[src:banana-chips/alaminos-longganisa] The sausages are celebrated in an annual "Longganisa Festival" in Alaminos.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] A **banana chip** (sometimes called **banana crisp**) is a deep-fried or dried, generally crispy slice of banana.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] It is usually made from firmer, starchier banana varieties (cooking bananas or plantains) like the saba and Nendran cultivars.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] It can be sweet or savory and can be covered with sugar, honey, salt, or various spices.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Banana chips are the only processed banana product with significant international trade.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] The main exporter of banana chips worldwide is the Philippines.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Export markets for banana chips are also established in Thailand, Indonesia and Malaysia.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Fried banana chips are usually produced from under-ripe banana slices deep-fried in sunflower oil or coconut oil.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] These chips are dry (like potato chips), contain about 4% water (table), and can be salted, spiced, sugar-coated, or jaggery-coated.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] If ripe dessert bananas are used, they come out soggy.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] They are used for desserts, not for dry chips.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Some varieties of banana chips can be produced using only food dehydration.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Banana slices that are only dehydrated are not dark yellow and crunchy but rather are brown, leathery, and chewy.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] They are very sweet and have an intense banana flavor.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] These are ideally made from fully ripe bananas.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Another kind is made by baking it in an oven, although this process may not result in the same intense banana flavor.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Dried banana chips are 4% water, 58% carbohydrates, 34% fat, and 2% protein.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] In a 100-gram reference amount, dried banana chips supply 520 calories and are a rich source (20% or more of the Daily Value, DV) of magnesium (21% DV) and vitamin B6 (20% DV), with moderate amounts of iron, copper, and potassium (10% to 11% DV) (table).
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Other micronutrients are in negligible amounts of the Daily Value (see nutrition table).
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] The Philippines is, by far, the main exporter of banana chips worldwide.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] It exports large quantities to more than 30 countries, including the United States, Canada, the European Union, Japan, Australia, South Korea, China, and Russia.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] The annual revenue for banana chip exports in the Philippines was approximately $35 million in 2009.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] There are many variants of banana chips in the Philippines, from traditional dishes like *pinasugbo* to modern versions coated in cheese powder.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Banana chips in the Philippines are made predominantly from saba or cardava bananas, with the latter preferred for commercial banana chips due to their larger sizes.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] For domestic production and home cooking, they are made directly by deep-frying fresh sliced bananas.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] For commercial banana chips for the export market, the main method of production is through osmotic dehydration followed by deep frying at 375 °F (191 °C) in coconut oil for 1 minute.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] The resulting chips are distinctively light-colored.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Fried plantain chips, known as **nenthra-kaaya oopperi** or **vazhaykka upperi** or **upperi** in Kerala, are fried in coconut oil.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Both ripe and unripe plantains are used for this type of chip preparation.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] The chips may be coated with masala or jaggery to form spicy and sweet variations.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Plain banana and plantain chips are called **pachkkaya varuthathu** and **kaya upperi**, respectively; sweet jaggery-banana chips are called **sharkara upperi** or **sharkkara varatty**.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] *Sharkara varatty* is more expensive than *upperi*.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] It is an integral part of the traditional Kerala meal called *sadya* served during weddings and festivals, such as Onam.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Bananas are native plants of Maritime Southeast Asia, and the people of the archipelago have developed many uses for them for ages, including as a snack.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] In Indonesia, a banana chip is called *kripik pisang*, and is considered a variant of crispy *kripik* (traditional chip or crisp).
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] *Kripik pisang* is a popular crispy snack and can be commonly found in Indonesia, although it seems to be more prevalent in Java and Sumatra.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] In North Maluku, popular with *pisang mulu bebek* is a duck-mouth-shaped banana chip.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] It is served with sambal, fried peanut, and fried anchovy.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] In Lampung, banana chips is combined with chocolate powder called *kripik pisang coklat*.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Usually, unripe green bananas are thinly sliced, soaked in a lime and salt water solution, and deep-fried as chips.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Unripe banana is well suited for deep frying due to its low content of water and sugar while having high starch content.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] *Pisang goreng* is another fried banana snack, although it is not thinly sliced and serves as a sweet hot snack.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] The chips are often part of muesli and nut mixes.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Other chips, such as patacones, are salty.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] Similar chips called chifle are made from plantains, the family of fruit that bananas come from.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] In tropical American cultures, all bananas are considered plantains, but not all plantains are bananas.
[src:banana-chips/banana-chips] These deep-fried plantain chips are also quite popular in the southeastern part of Mexico, especially in the state of Tabasco.
